							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistic which divides data into four same-sized parts for analysis</div>
<p>
In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics=
">statistics</a>, <b>quartiles</b> are a type of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Quantile" title=3D"Quantile">quantiles</a> which divide the =
number of data points into four parts, or <i>quarters</i>, of more-or-less =
equal size. The data must be ordered from smallest to largest to compute qu=
artiles; as such, quartiles are a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Order_statistic" title=3D"Order statistic">order statistic</a>. The=
 three quartiles, resulting in four data divisions, are as follows:
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Czech-wage-mode-median-mean-quantiles-percent=
iles.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedi=
a.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b2/Czech-wage-mode-median-mean-quantiles-pe=
rcentiles.png/250px-Czech-wage-mode-median-mean-quantiles-percentiles.png" =
decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"122" class=3D"mw-file-element" d=
ata-file-width=3D"1655" data-file-height=3D"808"></a><figcaption>Q1, Median=
 and Q3<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Quartile#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<ul><li>The first quartile (<i>Q</i><sub>1</sub>) is defined as the 25th <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Percentile" title=3D"Percentile">per=
centile</a>, where the lowest 25% data lies below this point. It is also kn=
own as the <i>lower</i> quartile.</li>
<li>The second quartile (<i>Q</i><sub>2</sub>) is the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=3D"Median">median</a> of a data set; thus=
 50% of the data lies below this point.</li>
<li>The third quartile (<i>Q</i><sub>3</sub>) is the 75th percentile, where=
 the lowest 75% data lies below this point. It is also known as the <i>uppe=
r</i> quartile.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartile#cite_note-:0-2"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Along with the minimum and maximum of the data (which are also quartiles=
), the three quartiles described above provide a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Five-number_summary" title=3D"Five-number summary">five-numb=
er summary</a> of the data. This summary is important in statistics because=
 it provides information about both the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mean_(Statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mean (Statistics)">=
center</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_dis=
persion" title=3D"Statistical dispersion">spread</a> of the data. Knowing t=
he lower and upper quartile provides information on how big the spread is a=
nd if the dataset is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skewness" tit=
le=3D"Skewness">skewed</a> toward one side. Since quartiles divide the numb=
er of data points evenly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rang=
e_(statistics)" title=3D"Range (statistics)">range</a> is generally not the=
 same between adjacent quartiles (i.e. usually (<i>Q</i><sub>3</sub> - <i>Q=
</i><sub>2</sub>) =E2=89=A0 (<i>Q</i><sub>2</sub> - <i>Q</i><sub>1</sub>)).=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interquartile_range" title=3D"Int=
erquartile range">Interquartile range</a> (IQR) is defined as the differenc=
e between the 75th and 25th percentiles or <i>Q</i><sub>3</sub> - <i>Q</i><=
sub>1</sub>. While the maximum and minimum also show the spread of the data=
, the upper and lower quartiles can provide more detailed information on th=
e location of specific data points, the presence of <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a> in the data, and =
the difference in spread between the middle 50% of the data and the outer d=
ata points.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartile#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definitions">Definitions</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuartile&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definitions"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Boxplot_vs_PDF.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descript=
ion"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1a/=
Boxplot_vs_PDF.svg/250px-Boxplot_vs_PDF.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"273" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"598" d=
ata-file-height=3D"652"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Boxplot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boxplot">Boxplot</a> (with qu=
artiles and an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interquartile_range=
" title=3D"Interquartile range">interquartile range</a>) and a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_density_function" title=3D"Probabi=
lity density function">probability density function</a> (pdf) of a normal N=
(0,1=CF=83<sup>2</sup>) population</figcaption></figure>
<table class=3D"wikitable">
<tbody><tr>
