</td></tr></tbody></table>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Computing_methods">Computin=
g methods</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQu=
artile&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Computing =
methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Discrete_distributions">Dis=
crete distributions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DQuartile&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: =
Discrete distributions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For discrete distributions, there is no universal agreement on selecting=
 the quartile values.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quartile#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_1">Method 1</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuartile&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Method 1"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ol><li>Use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" title=3D"M=
edian">median</a> to divide the ordered data set into two halves. The media=
n becomes the second quartile.
<ul><li>If there are an odd number of data points in the original ordered d=
ata set, <b>do not include</b> the median (the central value in the ordered=
 list) in either half.</li>
<li>If there are an even number of data points in the original ordered data=
 set, split this data set exactly in half.</li></ul></li>
<li>The lower quartile value is the median of the lower half of the data. T=
he upper quartile value is the median of the upper half of the data.</li></=
ol>
<p>This rule is employed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TI=
-83" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"TI-83">TI-83</a> calculator <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boxplot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Boxpl=
ot">boxplot</a> and "1-Var Stats" functions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_2">Method 2</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuartile&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Method 2"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ol><li>Use the median to divide the ordered data set into two halves. The =
median becomes the second quartile.
<ul><li>If there are an odd number of data points in the original ordered d=
ata set, <b>include</b> the median (the central value in the ordered list) =
in both halves.</li>
<li>If there are an even number of data points in the original ordered data=
 set, split this data set exactly in half.</li></ul></li>
<li>The lower quartile value is the median of the lower half of the data. T=
he upper quartile value is the median of the upper half of the data.</li></=
ol>
<p>The values found by this method are also known as "<a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Tukey" title=3D"John Tukey">Tukey</a>'s hinges";<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Quartile#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> see also <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Midhinge" title=3D"Midhinge">midhinge</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_3">Method 3</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuartile&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Method 3"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<ol><li>Use the median to divide the ordered data set into two halves. The =
median becomes the second quartile.
<ul><li>If there are odd numbers of data points, then go to the next step.<=
/li>
<li>If there are even numbers of data points, then the Method 3 starts off =
the same as the Method 1 or the Method 2 above and you can choose to includ=
e or not include the median as a new datapoint. If you choose to include th=
e median as the new datapoint, then proceed to the step 2 or 3 below becaus=
e you now have an odd number of datapoints. If you do not choose the median=
 as the new data point, then continue the Method 1 or 2 where you have star=
ted.</li></ul></li>
<li>If there are (4<i>n</i>+1) data points, then the lower quartile is 25% =
of the <i>n</i>th data value plus 75% of the (<i>n</i>+1)th data value; the=
 upper quartile is 75% of the (3<i>n</i>+1)th data point plus 25% of the (3=
<i>n</i>+2)th data point.</li>
<li>If there are (4<i>n</i>+3) data points, then the lower quartile is 75% =
of the (<i>n</i>+1)th data value plus 25% of the (<i>n</i>+2)th data value;=
 the upper quartile is 25% of the (3<i>n</i>+2)th data point plus 75% of th=
e (3<i>n</i>+3)th data point.</li></ol>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Method_4">Method 4</h4><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DQuartile&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Method 4"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If we have an ordered dataset <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-e=
lement-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" =
style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"=
 alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>x</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
