Q_{1}}"></span>), may be used to characterize the data when there may be ex=
tremities that skew the data; the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Interquartile_range" title=3D"Interquartile range">interquartile range</a> =
is a relatively <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robust_statistic" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Robust statistic">robust statistic</a> (also=
 sometimes called "resistance") compared to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Range_(statistics)" title=3D"Range (statistics)">range</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" title=3D"Sta=
ndard deviation">standard deviation</a>. There is also a mathematical metho=
d to check for outliers and determining "fences", upper and lower limits fr=
om which to check for outliers.
</p><p>After determining the first (lower) and third (upper) quartiles (<sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
