utliers</figcaption></figure></dd></dl>
<p>The lower fence is the "lower limit" and the upper fence is the "upper l=
imit" of data, and any data lying outside these defined bounds can be consi=
dered an outlier. The fences provide a guideline by which to define an <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outlier</a>=
, which may be defined in other ways. The fences define a "range" outside w=
hich an outlier exists; a way to picture this is a boundary of a fence. It =
is common for the lower and upper fences along with the outliers to be repr=
esented by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Box_plot" title=3D"Bo=
x plot">boxplot</a>. For the boxplot shown on the right, only the vertical =
heights correspond to the visualized data set while horizontal width of the=
 box is irrelevant. Outliers located outside the fences in a boxplot can be=
 marked as any choice of symbol, such as an "x" or "o". The fences are some=
times also referred to as "whiskers" while the entire plot visual is called=
 a "box-and-whisker" plot.
</p><p>When spotting an outlier in the data set by calculating the interqua=
rtile ranges and boxplot features, it might be easy to mistakenly view it a=
s evidence that the population is non-normal or that the sample is contamin=
ated. However, this method should not take place of a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothesis_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hypothe=
sis test">hypothesis test</a> for determining normality of the population. =
The significance of the outliers varies depending on the sample size. If th=
e sample is small, then it is more probable to get interquartile ranges tha=
t are unrepresentatively small, leading to narrower fences. Therefore, it w=
ould be more likely to find data that are marked as outliers.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quart=
ile#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
